      "role": "user",
      "content": "well i get that both have frameworks, but u kind of just said the humanitarian one is \"compelling\" while the border one is just a \"duty.\" isnt it true that prioritizing borders over actual human lives is fundamentally less moral? like, if you have to choose between a policy and a person's life, it seems like a no-brainer which one is the \"right\" moral stance. don't u think?",
